Mr. Wilde.


914
1:8:15,983 --> 1:8:18,919
My dear man,
what are you talking about?


915
1:8:18,919 --> 1:8:22,69
At once, please.


916
1:8:22,69 --> 1:8:38,72
What's the matter? My father
cracking the whip downstairs, is he?


917
1:8:38,72 --> 1:8:40,908
- My lord.
- Bosie.


918
1:8:40,908 --> 1:8:43,611
You're not frightened of what
this little man thinks, are you?


919
1:8:43,611 --> 1:8:52,553
I think the pleasures of the evening
should be resumed elsewhere.


920
1:8:52,553 --> 1:8:54,755
You're such a coward.


921
1:8:54,755 --> 1:8:56,957
You say you despise convention...


922
1:8:56,957 --> 1:9:0,561
but you're the most
conventional man I know.


923
1:9:0,561 --> 1:9:11,905
Come on then.
If we're going, let's go.


924
1:9:11,905 --> 1:9:14,275
Until tomorrow, Tommy.


925
1:9:14,275 --> 1:9:16,41
Good-bye, sir.


926
1:9:16,41 --> 1:9:24,218
I goes in, and there's
all this tropical fruit laid out.


927
1:9:24,218 --> 1:9:27,221
Wait a minute, Oscar!


928
1:9:27,221 --> 1:9:31,325
Alfred, how nice to see you.
And Charlie, looking so well.


929
1:9:31,325 --> 1:9:33,861
I'm afraid I'm busy this evening,
but we must have dinner again soon.


930
1:9:33,861 --> 1:9:39,333
It's not a question of dinner.
I got a letter of yours to Lord Alfred.


931
1:9:39,333 --> 1:9:42,169
It's a nice letter, Oscar.
Beautiful.


932
1:9:42,169 --> 1:9:46,73
"Lips like roses. The madness
of kisses in ancient Greece."


933
1:9:46,73 --> 1:9:48,242
Then I expect
it's one of my prose poems.


934
1:9:48,242 --> 1:9:49,943
There's a gentleman's
offered me 60 pounds for it.


935
1:9:49,943 --> 1:9:52,913
Then you must accept, Alfred.
I've never received so large a sum...


936
1:9:52,913 --> 1:9:55,215
for a prose work of that length
in all my life.


937
1:9:55,215 --> 1:9:58,886
Tell him I'm delighted that someone
in England values my work so highly.


938
1:9:58,886 --> 1:10:0,954
- Well, he's gone away.
- He's gone to the country.


939
1:10:0,954 --> 1:10:5,859
Well, I'm sure
he'll be back soon.


940
1:10:5,859 --> 1:10:10,264
Oscar, look. You couldn't
let us have something, could you?


941
1:10:10,264 --> 1:10:14,435
Bit short at the moment.
You know.


942
1:10:14,435 --> 1:10:17,37
Of course. Of course.


943
1:10:17,37 --> 1:10:19,94
Here's half a sovereign. Now you mind
you take good care of that letter.


944
1:10:19,94 --> 1:10:24,345
Lord Alfred is going to publish it
in sonnet form in his new magazine.


945
1:10:24,345 --> 1:10:29,283
For fuck's sake.


946
1:10:29,283 --> 1:10:31,552
It's no good
trying to rent you.


947
1:10:31,552 --> 1:10:34,521
You just laugh at us.


948
1:10:34,521 --> 1:10:37,624
- Here.
- Thank you.


949
1:10:37,624 --> 1:10:42,229
He can be very careless,
Lord Alfred.


950
1:10:42,229 --> 1:10:44,698
What a wonderfully
wicked life you lead.


951
1:10:44,698 --> 1:10:51,805
You boys. You boys.


952
1:10:51,805 --> 1:10:54,808
- Where is he?
- Mr. Wilde is not receiving visitors.


953
1:10:54,808 --> 1:10:57,311
- Where is he?
- He's busy, sir. I cannot...


954
1:10:57,311 --> 1:11:2,383
I wish you would get out of my way.
Get out of my way!


955
1:11:2,383 --> 1:11:4,918
Excuse me, sir,
there's a gentleman...


956
1:11:4,918 --> 1:11:7,287
You!


957
1:11:7,287 --> 1:11:10,224
Listen to me.


958
1:11:10,224 --> 1:11:14,128
You're a bugger!


959
1:11:14,128 --> 1:11:17,464
I don't allow people to talk to me like
that in my house, Lord Queensberry...


960
1:11:17,464 --> 1:11:20,0
or anywhere else.


961
1:11:20,0 --> 1:11:23,504
I suppose you've come to apologize for
the lies you've been spreading about me?


962
1:11:23,504 --> 1:11:27,708
I've come to tell you
to leave my son alone, you sodomite.


963
1:11:27,708 --> 1:11:31,779
The marquis appears to be very obsessed
with other people's sexual activities.


964
1:11:31,779 --> 1:11:33,847
Has it anything to do
with his new wife...


965
1:11:33,847 --> 1:11:37,418
I wonder, and the fact that she's
seeking divorce for non-consummation?


966
1:11:37,418 --> 1:11:40,521
Unless you swear that you'll have
nothing more to do with Bosie...


967
1:11:40,521 --> 1:11:42,89
I shall go to Scotland Yard.


968
1:11:42,89 --> 1:11:44,491
You can go to the devil.


969
1:11:44,491 --> 1:11:47,27
You and your...
Who is this gargoyle?


970
1:11:47,27 --> 1:11:51,64
You're a queer!
And a sham! A poseur!


971
1:11:51,64 --> 1:11:56,69
If I catch you and Bosie together again,
I'll give you such a thrashing.


972
1:11:56,69 --> 1:11:59,44
I believe Lord Queensberry
once invented some rules for boxing.


973
1:11:59,44 --> 1:12:1,375
I've no idea what they are...


974
1:12:1,375 --> 1:12:3,444
but the Oscar Wilde rule
is to shoot on sight.


975
1:12:3,444 --> 1:12:6,213
- Now, kindly leave my house.
- You can shut up!


976
1:12:6,213 --> 1:12:13,754
I shall leave
when I'm damn well ready.


977
1:12:13,754 --> 1:12:16,457
It's a scandal
what you've been doing.


978
1:12:16,457 --> 1:12:19,693
All the scandal is your own.


979
1:12:19,693 --> 1:12:22,129
Your treatment of your wives...


980
1:12:22,129 --> 1:12:24,131
your neglect of your children...


981
1:12:24,131 --> 1:12:27,501
and, above all,
the depraved insistence...


982
1:12:27,501 --> 1:12:32,773
that they be as tyrannical
and unloving as you are yourself.


983
1:12:32,773 --> 1:12:35,876
Arthur, this is
the Marquis of Queensberry...


984
1:12:35,876 --> 1:12:40,547
the most infamous brute
and the least tender father in London.


985
1:12:40,547 --> 1:12:45,619
Never let him
into my house again.


986
1:12:45,619 --> 1:12:49,256
Very well then.


987
1:12:49,256 --> 1:13:37,204
Let's get out of this stew.


988
1:13:37,204 --> 1:13:39,473
- Out of the way, then!
- I'm sorry, sir!


989
1:13:39,473 --> 1:13:49,783
I'm very sorry,
but it's just not possible!


990
1:13:49,783 --> 1:13:52,753
What are you doing?
Rotten vegetables?


991
1:13:52,753 --> 1:13:54,655
Give that to Oscar Wilde.


992
1:13:54,655 --> 1:13:57,791
Thank you, sir.
We'll take care of it.


993
1:13:57,791 --> 1:14:2,629
I wanted to give it to him
personally as a bouquet.


994
1:14:2,629 --> 1:14:7,0
I daresay you did, sir,
but you're not going to.


995
1:14:7,0 --> 1:14:11,4
He's a cur and a sod!


996
1:14:11,4 --> 1:14:12,739
And a bugger!


997
1:14:12,739 --> 1:14:17,578
You remember that!


998
1:14:17,578 --> 1:14:20,581
I always told you, Gwendolen,
my name is Ernest, didn't I?


999
1:14:20,581 --> 1:14:22,916
Well, it is Ernest after all.


1000
1:14:22,916 --> 1:14:26,86
I mean, it naturally is Ernest.


1001
1:14:26,86 --> 1:14:29,69
Yes, I remember now
that the general was called Ernest.


1002
1:14:29,69 --> 1:14:35,495
I knew I had some particular reason
for disliking the name.


1003
1:14:35,495 --> 1:14:39,99
Ernest! My own Ernest!


1004
1:14:39,99 --> 1:14:42,803
I knew from the first
you could have had no other name.


1005
1:14:42,803 --> 1:14:46,6
Gwendolen, it's a terrible thing
for a man to find out suddenly...


1006
1:14:46,6 --> 1:14:50,43
that all his life he's been
speaking nothing but the truth.


1007
1:14:50,43 --> 1:14:52,45
Can you forgive me?


1008
1:14:52,45 --> 1:14:55,749
I can, for I feel
you are sure to change.


1009
1:14:55,749 --> 1:14:58,385
- My own one!
- Laetitia.


1010
1:14:58,385 --> 1:15:0,387
Frederick! At last!


1011
1:15:0,387 --> 1:15:5,626
- Cecily! At last!
- Gwendolen! At last!


1012
1:15:5,626 --> 1:15:11,31
My nephew, you seem to be
displaying signs of triviality.


1013
1:15:11,31 --> 1:15:13,433
On the contrary, Aunt Augusta...


1014
1:15:13,433 --> 1:15:16,637
I've now realized
for the first time in my life...


1015
1:15:16,637 --> 1:15:48,335
the vital importance
of being earnest.


1016
1:15:48,335 --> 1:15:50,837
Allen, you were wonderful!
Thank you all so much.


1017
1:15:50,837 --> 1:15:53,306
They're calling for you.
You must come on. Curtain, curtain.


1018
1:15:53,306 --> 1:16:43,29
- No, no, George, no, no.
- Come on!


1019
1:16:43,29 --> 1:16:48,328
- Mr. Wilde, sir.
- Yes?


1020
1:16:48,328 --> 1:17:1,875
- For you.
- Thank you.


1021
1:17:1,875 --> 1:17:5,512
"For Oscar Wilde...


1022
1:17:5,512 --> 1:17:6,947
Ponce," is it?


1023
1:17:6,947 --> 1:17:9,316
"Ponce and 'somdomite."'


1024
1:17:9,316 --> 1:17:13,553
"Posing as a sodomite."
He's illiterate... illiterate, ignorant.


1025
1:17:13,553 --> 1:17:16,656
- It's hideous.
- We've got him now, Robbie.


1026
1:17:16,656 --> 1:17:18,625
He wrote it down.
The porter read it.


1027
1:17:18,625 --> 1:17:21,495
That makes it a public libel.
Now we can take him to court.


1028
1:17:21,495 --> 1:17:26,833
For God's sake.


1029
1:17:26,833 --> 1:17:29,936
Oscar, you mustn't do that.
That would be... I mean...


1030
1:17:29,936 --> 1:17:32,405
We've just been waiting for a chance
to get him in the dock...


1031
1:17:32,405 --> 1:17:35,342
and show the world what a swine
and shit he's always been.


1032
1:17:35,342 --> 1:17:39,346
- To me, my mother, my brothers.
- But he'll plead justification.


1033
1:17:39,346 --> 1:17:42,182
He'll call all the renters
as witnesses for the defense.


1034
1:17:42,182 --> 1:17:45,85
Of course he won't.
He doesn't know what a renter is.


1035
1:17:45,85 --> 1:17:49,656
I hear he's had detectives following you
ever since you came back from Egypt.


1036
1:17:49,656 --> 1:17:53,627
He can't prove anything.
But we can.


1037
1:17:53,627 --> 1:17:55,929
We can prove he's the vilest man
that ever walked the earth.


1038
1:17:55,929 --> 1:17:57,931
Tear the card up, Oscar.
Pretend you never got it.


1039
1:17:57,931 --> 1:18:1,34
Are you mad?
That's our main piece of evidence.


1040
1:18:1,34 --> 1:18:3,67
I'm sure if Oscar went abroad
for a few months...


1041
1:18:3,67 --> 1:18:5,806
lived on royalties
while your father calms down...


1042
1:18:5,806 --> 1:18:8,542
- Whose side are you on?
- Bosie, if this goes to court...


1043
1:18:8,542 --> 1:18:10,644
Oscar will have to tell lies...


1044
1:18:10,644 --> 1:18:13,58
perjure himself...
everything will come out.


1045
1:18:13,58 --> 1:18:16,483
Whatever the result,
it will be utter disaster.


1046
1:18:16,483 --> 1:18:18,218
You're an enemy then.


1047
1:18:18,218 --> 1:18:22,322
No, no, Bosie, please.
Robbie...


1048
1:18:22,322 --> 1:18:25,992
you're a dear boy, but I can't
even think of leaving the country.


1049
1:18:25,992 --> 1:18:31,164
As a matter of fact, I can't even
leave this hotel. I can't pay the bill.


1050
1:18:31,164 --> 1:18:34,0
We can raise you money,
for heaven's sake.


1051
1:18:34,0 --> 1:18:36,736
Anyway, what about
your royalties?


1052
1:18:36,736 --> 1:18:39,94
We shall need all the money
we can get for the libel case.


1053
1:18:39,94 --> 1:18:44,611
My father can't go on making
all our lives a torment like this.


1054
1:18:44,611 --> 1:18:47,681
Oscar, I beg you.


1055
1:18:47,681 --> 1:18:49,449
I'm not going to run away, Robbie.


1056
1:18:49,449 --> 1:18:52,886
I'm not going to hide.
That would be the English thing to do.


1057
1:18:52,886 --> 1:18:56,456
If you take Queensberry to court,
all hell will break loose.


1058
1:18:56,456 --> 1:19:0,126
All my life I've fought
against the English vice:


1059
1:19:0,126 --> 1:19:3,163
Hypocrisy...
not that that's the point.


1060
1:19:3,163 --> 1:19:7,667
The point is, Queensberry's already
caused the death of one of his sons.


1061
1:19:7,667 --> 1:19:13,707
If I don't try and stop him now,
whom will he harm next?


1062
1:19:13,707 --> 1:19:16,877
<i>He's avoiding me, Robbie.</i>


1063
1:19:16,877 --> 1:19:20,714
I know what everyone's saying,
but it's not true.


1064
1:19:20,714 --> 1:19:24,251
It's not true.


1065
1:19:24,251 --> 1:19:28,922
- Is it?
- Of course not.


1066
1:19:28,922 --> 1:19:32,659
Oh, it's so shaming.


1067
1:19:32,659 --> 1:19:37,3
No, I find it easier to stand.


1068
1:19:37,3 --> 1:19:41,434
I'm going to Torquay for a month,
try to get my back right.


1069
1:19:41,434 --> 1:19:45,5
- Oscar's been so busy...
- I'm sure he'll be terribly upset...


1070
1:19:45,5 --> 1:19:49,843
when he knows you've been
in so much pain.


1071
1:19:49,843 --> 1:19:53,847
The truth is,
I need some money.


1072
1:19:53,847 --> 1:19:57,784
Not even sure where he is
to ask for it.


1073
1:19:57,784 --> 1:20:0,687
It does seem rather hard when he's
having such an extraordinary success.


1074
1:20:0,687 --> 1:20:6,26
I think I can find him.


1075
1:20:6,26 --> 1:20:8,628
I keep hearing these stories
about Bosie and his father.


1076
1:20:8,628 --> 1:20:14,801
- I'm sure you don't want to...
- Oh, yes. I do.


1077
1:20:14,801 --> 1:20:19,439
Men think women should be
protected by not knowing.


1078
1:20:19,439 --> 1:20:24,878
Not knowing only makes it worse.


1079
1:20:24,878 --> 1:20:29,883
Is there going to be trouble?


1080
1:20:29,883 --> 1:20:33,653
I hope not.


1081
1:20:33,653 --> 1:20:36,222
<i>I believe a prosecution
would certainly succeed...</i>


1082
1:20:36,222 --> 1:20:38,258
provided...
and I stress this...


1083
1:20:38,258 --> 1:20:42,295
provided there is no truth whatever in
the accusation made by Lord Queensberry.


1084
1:20:42,295 --> 1:20:46,232
Of course
there's no truth in it.


1085
1:20:46,232 --> 1:21:1,14
Then so long as I have Mr. Wilde's
assurance that that is indeed the case.


1086
1:21:1,14 --> 1:21:4,918
There is no truth
in the accusation whatever.


1087
1:21:4,918 --> 1:21:10,29
Good. Excellent.


1088
1:21:10,29 --> 1:21:14,127
The defense, I understand,
will be led by Mr. Edward Carson.


1089
1:21:14,127 --> 1:21:18,231
Old Ned? I was at college
with him in Dublin.


1090
1:21:18,231 --> 1:21:24,804
No doubt he will perform his task with
all the bitterness of an old friend.


1091
1:21:24,804 --> 1:21:27,54
In writing a book or a play,
I'm concerned entirely with literature...


1092
1:21:27,54 --> 1:21:31,778
with art... I do not aim
at doing good or evil...


1093
1:21:31,778 --> 1:21:34,147
but at making a thing that will have
some quality of beauty.


1094
1:21:34,147 --> 1:21:39,619
Well, listen, sir. Here is
one of your pieces of literature.


1095
1:21:39,619 --> 1:21:42,555
"Wickedness is a myth
invented by good people...


1096
1:21:42,555 --> 1:21:49,629
to account for the curious
attractiveness of others."


1097
1:21:49,629 --> 1:21:51,297
Do you think that true?


1098
1:21:51,297 --> 1:21:53,8
Oh, I rarely think
anything I write is true.


1099
1:21:53,8 --> 1:22:2,308
"If one tells the truth, one is sure,
sooner or later, to be found out."


1100
1:22:2,308 --> 1:22:6,46
That is a pleasing paradox, but
I do not set store by it as an axiom.


1101
1:22:6,46 --> 1:22:8,581
Is it good for the young?


1102
1:22:8,581 --> 1:22:11,918
Anything is good that stimulates
thought, at whatever age.


1103
1:22:11,918 --> 1:22:13,92
Whether moral or immoral?


1104
1:22:13,92 --> 1:22:16,956
There's no such thing
as morality or immorality in thought.


1105
1:22:16,956 --> 1:22:19,993
What about this then?


1106
1:22:19,993 --> 1:22:24,531
"Pleasure is the only thing
one should live for."


1107
1:22:24,531 --> 1:22:28,168
I think that the realization of
one's self is the prime aim of life...


1108
1:22:28,168 --> 1:22:32,572
and that to realize through pleasure is
finer than to do so through pain.


1109
1:22:32,572 --> 1:22:39,479
I am, on this point, entirely on
the side of the ancients, the Greeks.


1110
1:22:39,479 --> 1:22:42,749
<i>How long have you known
Alfred Taylor?</i>


1111
1:22:42,749 --> 1:22:45,752
<i>About two years,
two-and-a-half years.</i>


1112
1:22:45,752 --> 1:22:49,622
- Is he an intimate friend of yours?
- I wouldn't call him that, no.


1113
1:22:49,622 --> 1:22:52,292
But you went often to his rooms?


1114
1:22:52,292 --> 1:22:54,694
About seven or eight times,
perhaps.


1115
1:22:54,694 --> 1:23:1,935
Did you know Mr. Taylor kept
ladies' dresses in his rooms?


1116
1:23:1,935 --> 1:23:6,873
Did you know he was notorious
for introducing young men to older men?


1117
1:23:6,873 --> 1:23:10,21
I never heard it in my life.


1118
1:23:10,21 --> 1:23:13,279
Has he introduced
young men to you?


1119
1:23:13,279 --> 1:23:15,281
Yes.


1120
1:23:15,281 --> 1:23:18,952
- How many young men?
- About five.


1121
1:23:18,952 --> 1:23:23,69
- What were their occupations?
- I really don't know.


1122
1:23:23,69 --> 1:23:26,459
Oh, well, let me tell you,
Mr. Wilde.


1123
1:23:26,459 --> 1:23:30,43
You met a man called
Charles Parker there, I believe.


1124
1:23:30,43 --> 1:23:31,598
Yes.


1125
1:23:31,598 --> 1:23:34,534
Charles Parker is...


1126
1:23:34,534 --> 1:23:37,937
a gentleman's valet.


1127
1:23:37,937 --> 1:23:39,939
You met his brother there
too, I believe.


1128
1:23:39,939 --> 1:23:44,31
- Yes.
- He is a groom.


1129
1:23:44,31 --> 1:23:46,713
I didn't care tuppence
what they were.


1130
1:23:46,713 --> 1:23:51,484
I liked them. I have a passion
to civilize the community.


1131
1:23:51,484 --> 1:23:55,922
I recognize no social distinctions
at all of any kind.


1132
1:23:55,922 --> 1:23:58,24
To me, youth...
the mere fact of youth...


1133
1:23:58,24 --> 1:24:2,295
is so wonderful that I would sooner
talk to a young man for half an hour...


1134
1:24:2,295 --> 1:24:6,799
than, well, than be
cross-examined in court.


1135
1:24:6,799 --> 1:24:9,903
So, do I understand that...


1136
1:24:9,903 --> 1:24:13,473
even a boy you might pick up in the
street would be a pleasing companion?


1137
1:24:13,473 --> 1:24:17,777
I would talk to a street Arab
with pleasure if he would talk to me.


1138
1:24:17,777 --> 1:24:19,779
- And take him to your rooms?
- Yes.


1139
1:24:19,779 --> 1:24:24,217
And then commit
improprieties with him?


1140
1:24:24,217 --> 1:24:29,88
Certainly not.


1141
1:24:29,88 --> 1:24:32,859
<i>You withdraw your libel action
against Lord Queensberry.</i>


1142
1:24:32,859 --> 1:24:34,928
Well and good.


1143
1:24:34,928 --> 1:24:38,364
But there remains the question
of the evidence...


1144
1:24:38,364 --> 1:24:41,968
Lord Queensberry's evidence
against you.


1145
1:24:41,968 --> 1:24:47,707
My information is that the Crown
wishes to pursue the matter.


1146
1:24:47,707 --> 1:24:52,845
In which case, an arrest
and a charge of gross indecency...


1147
1:24:52,845 --> 1:24:54,948
are certain to follow.


1148
1:24:54,948 --> 1:24:58,952
The maximum sentence
is two years hard labor.


1149
1:24:58,952 --> 1:25:2,989
Nine months hard labor
is reckoned to be more...


1150
1:25:2,989 --> 1:25:4,991
than a man of our background...


1151
1:25:4,991 --> 1:25:9,495
can survive.


1152
1:25:9,495 --> 1:25:11,531
The children, the boys...


1153
1:25:11,531 --> 1:25:14,634
- I must go and see them.
- You have no time for that.


1154
1:25:14,634 --> 1:25:19,72
But my wife...
I have to say good-bye to my wife.


1155
1:25:19,72 --> 1:25:21,841
Unless you positively wish
to subject her...


1156
1:25:21,841 --> 1:25:24,244
to the further humiliation
of seeing you arrested...


1157
1:25:24,244 --> 1:25:27,58
and taken away
in front of the gutter press...


1158
1:25:27,58 --> 1:25:36,256
<i>Mr. Wilde, you must go.</i>


1159
1:25:36,256 --> 1:25:40,526
Oscar, you must take that train.


1160
1:25:40,526 --> 1:25:43,563
Practically everyone
you know will be on it.


1161
1:25:43,563 --> 1:25:52,839
At least 600 single gentlemen,
all in abject terror of arrest.


1162
1:25:52,839 --> 1:25:57,71
Where your life leads you,
you must go.


1163
1:25:57,71 --> 1:25:59,879
<i>I defy society.</i>


1164
1:25:59,879 --> 1:26:3,349
Tell him to go.


1165
1:26:3,349 --> 1:26:7,553
He must save himself.


1166
1:26:7,553 --> 1:26:9,656
Tell him to go abroad.


1167
1:26:9,656 --> 1:26:13,426
I've been telling him all day.


1168
1:26:13,426 --> 1:26:22,235
He won't budge.


1169
1:26:22,235 --> 1:26:26,572
People have never understood
the courage he needed to be himself.


1170
1:26:26,572 --> 1:26:28,808
You must go abroad too.


1171
1:26:28,808 --> 1:26:34,414
We must all go abroad at once.


1172
1:26:34,414 --> 1:26:39,252
Oscar says, will you
tell the boys good-bye.


1173
1:26:39,252 --> 1:26:45,124
I need to go through his papers.


1174
1:26:45,124 --> 1:26:48,961
You know,
I was always too silent.


1175
1:26:48,961 --> 1:26:56,402
If I'd known...


1176
1:26:56,402 --> 1:26:58,504
If I'd only spoken up.


1177
1:26:58,504 --> 1:27:2,342
It wouldn't have made
any difference.


1178
1:27:2,342 --> 1:27:5,78
Perhaps not...


1179
1:27:5,78 --> 1:27:31,838
but at least I wouldn't
blame myself now.


1180
1:27:31,838 --> 1:27:35,208
<i>You're an Irish gentleman.
Of course, you must stay.</i>


1181
1:27:35,208 --> 1:27:37,61
Your father fought
when he was libeled.


1182
1:27:37,61 --> 1:27:40,613
<i>- I was in the courts myself. I fought...
- Yes, I know, Madre.</i>


1183
1:27:40,613 --> 1:27:44,517
You will fight these
English philistines, and you'll win.


1184
1:27:44,517 --> 1:27:49,389
And even if you lose...
if you go to prison...


1185
1:27:49,389 --> 1:27:52,492
you'll always be my son.


1186
1:27:52,492 --> 1:27:56,295
Of course, it's too late
to change that now.


1187
1:27:56,295 --> 1:27:58,131
If you go, Oscar...


1188
1:27:58,131 --> 1:28:0,6
I'll never speak to you again.


1189
1:28:0,6 --> 1:28:5,571
No one will ever speak
to me again, whatever I do.


1190
1:28:5,571 --> 1:28:8,908
<i>Of course I'm your son, Madre...</i>


1191
1:28:8,908 --> 1:28:12,245
which is why,
even if I lose...


1192
1:28:12,245 --> 1:28:17,617
the English
will never forget me.


1193
1:28:17,617 --> 1:28:48,381
My darling.


1194
1:28:48,381 --> 1:28:52,118
Get out of my way.
Get out! Out!


1195
1:28:52,118 --> 1:29:2,328
Take me away at once!


1196
1:29:2,328 --> 1:29:4,53
Lady Wilde. Lady Wilde!


1197
1:29:4,53 --> 1:29:7,567
Have you anything to say about
your son's disgrace, Lady Wilde?


1198
1:29:7,567 --> 1:29:17,76
<i>Have you anything to say?</i>


1199
1:29:17,76 --> 1:29:25,284
Come in.


1200
1:29:25,284 --> 1:29:28,754
Mr. Wilde, I believe.


1201
1:29:28,754 --> 1:29:29,922
Yes, yes.


1202
1:29:29,922 --> 1:29:32,225
We have a warrant here
for your arrest...


1203
1:29:32,225 --> 1:29:43,169
on a charge
of committing indecent acts.


1204
1:29:43,169 --> 1:29:45,438
<i>I recommend Switzerland
as soon as possible.</i>


1205
1:29:45,438 --> 1:29:50,743
You will have to change
your name, of course.


1206
1:29:50,743 --> 1:29:52,78
I can't.


1207
1:29:52,78 --> 1:29:54,78
My dear Constance,
the name of Wilde will be...


1208
1:29:54,78 --> 1:29:56,949
a word of execration
for the next thousand years.


1209
1:29:56,949 --> 1:30:0,686
You can't possibly let your boys grow up
with people knowing who they are.


1210
1:30:0,686 --> 1:30:2,688
Think of their lives at school.


1211
1:30:2,688 --> 1:30:6,459
Thank you for your advice.


1212
1:30:6,459 --> 1:30:8,694
I'm sorry our friendship
has to end like this.


1213
1:30:8,694 --> 1:30:12,965
- Oh, you will always be my friend.
- I am still Oscar's wife.


1214
1:30:12,965 --> 1:30:17,336
That must cease forthwith.
Forthwith. Do you understand?


1215
1:30:17,336 --> 1:30:20,306
Anybody who has anything
to do with Oscar from now on...


1216
1:30:20,306 --> 1:30:23,342
will never be received
in society again...


1217
1:30:23,342 --> 1:30:29,749
ever.


1218
1:30:29,749 --> 1:30:42,395
Oh, God, Ada.
What is going to happen to him?


1219
1:30:42,395 --> 1:30:44,564
That's Oscar Wilde's boy.


1220
1:30:44,564 --> 1:30:47,199
Oscar, you must let me
in the witness box.


1221
1:30:47,199 --> 1:30:49,669
If the jury can only hear
what I have to say...


1222
1:30:49,669 --> 1:30:51,938
Bosie, darling boy.


1223
1:30:51,938 --> 1:30:55,7
As soon as they see you
in all your golden youth...


1224
1:30:55,7 --> 1:30:57,243
and me in all my corruption...


1225
1:30:57,243 --> 1:31:0,713
You didn't corrupt me.
I corrupted you, if anything.


1226
1:31:0,713 --> 1:31:2,715
That's not how it will seem.


1227
1:31:2,715 --> 1:31:6,18
But I must have my say.
It's outrageous.


1228
1:31:6,18 --> 1:31:9,221
Everyone else has said everything,
anything that came into his head.


1229
1:31:9,221 --> 1:31:11,991
But I'm the person
all this is about.


1230
1:31:11,991 --> 1:31:14,527
It's me my father wants
to get at, not you.


1231
1:31:14,527 --> 1:31:17,29
It's outrageous
that I can't have my say.


1232
1:31:17,29 --> 1:31:21,601
It won't help, Bosie.
It may actually make things worse.


1233
1:31:21,601 --> 1:31:27,907
But my father will win.
I can't endure my father winning.


1234
1:31:27,907 --> 1:31:30,209
You must go away, dear boy.


1235
1:31:30,209 --> 1:31:36,616
I couldn't bear for them
to arrest you.


1236
1:31:36,616 --> 1:31:42,388
I can't bear what they're
saying about you in court.


1237
1:31:42,388 --> 1:31:46,392
Jesus Christ.


1238
1:31:46,392 --> 1:31:48,628
Good-bye, Bosie, dear boy.


1239
1:31:48,628 --> 1:31:51,897
Don't let anyone, anything,
ever change your feeling for me...


1240
1:31:51,897 --> 1:31:53,633
change your love.


1241
1:31:53,633 --> 1:31:56,636
- See you next time.
- Time's up, my lord.


1242
1:31:56,636 --> 1:32:11,751
Oscar, never. They never will.
I won't let them.


1243
1:32:11,751 --> 1:32:14,52
<i>You've been a great deal
in the company of Lord Alfred Douglas?</i>


1244
1:32:14,52 --> 1:32:17,39
Oh, yes.


1245
1:32:17,39 --> 1:32:20,526
- Did he read his poems to you?
- Yes.


1246
1:32:20,526 --> 1:32:23,963
So, you can perhaps
understand that...


1247
1:32:23,963 --> 1:32:26,399
some of his verses...


1248
1:32:26,399 --> 1:32:32,772
would not be acceptable to a reader
with an ordinary balance to mind?


1249
1:32:32,772 --> 1:32:34,74
I'm not prepared to say.


1250
1:32:34,74 --> 1:32:37,943
It's a question of taste
and temperament...


1251
1:32:37,943 --> 1:32:40,179
and individuality.


1252
1:32:40,179 --> 1:32:43,315
I should say that one man's poetry
is another man's poison.


1253
1:32:43,315 --> 1:32:45,851
Yes, I daresay.


1254
1:32:45,851 --> 1:32:48,521
But in this poem
by Lord Alfred Douglas...


1255
1:32:48,521 --> 1:32:50,99
"Two Loves"...


1256
1:32:50,99 --> 1:32:52,992
there is one love,
true love...


1257
1:32:52,992 --> 1:32:56,796
which... and I quote...


1258
1:32:56,796 --> 1:33:0,599
"fills the hearts of boy and girl
with mutual flame."


1259
1:33:0,599 --> 1:33:4,87
And, there is another:


1260
1:33:4,87 --> 1:33:11,444
"I am the love
that dare not speak its name."


1261
1:33:11,444 --> 1:33:14,58
Was that poem explained to you?


1262
1:33:14,58 --> 1:33:18,5
- I think it's clear.
- There's no doubt as to what it means?


1263
1:33:18,5 --> 1:33:19,819
Most certainly not.


1264
1:33:19,819 --> 1:33:22,855
So, is it not clear
that the love described...


1265
1:33:22,855 --> 1:33:30,996
relates to natural
and unnatural love?


1266
1:33:30,996 --> 1:33:47,68
Then what is the love
that dare not speak its name?


1267
1:33:47,68 --> 1:33:51,55
The love that dare not
speak its name...


1268
1:33:51,55 --> 1:33:54,22
in this century...


1269
1:33:54,22 --> 1:33:56,889
is such a great affection...


1270
1:33:56,889 --> 1:34:0,459
of an elder for a younger man...


1271
1:34:0,459 --> 1:34:3,62
as there was between
David and Jonathan...


1272
1:34:3,62 --> 1:34:8,0
such as Plato made
the very basis of his philosophy...


1273
1:34:8,0 --> 1:34:11,837
and such as you may find in
the sonnets of Michelangelo...


1274
1:34:11,837 --> 1:34:15,608
and Shakespeare.


1275
1:34:15,608 --> 1:34:20,246
It is, in this century,
misunderstood...


1276
1:34:20,246 --> 1:34:23,883
so much misunderstood
that it may be described as...


1277
1:34:23,883 --> 1:34:26,786
the love that dare not
speak its name.


1278
1:34:26,786 --> 1:34:32,124
And, on account of it,
I am placed where I am now.


1279
1:34:32,124 --> 1:34:36,562
It is beautiful.
It is fine.


1280
1:34:36,562 --> 1:34:40,132
It is the noblest form
of affection.


1281
1:34:40,132 --> 1:34:44,703
There's nothing unnatural
about it.


1282
1:34:44,703 --> 1:34:47,239
It is intellectual...


1283
1:34:47,239 --> 1:34:51,177
and it repeatedly exists
between an elder and a younger man...


1284
1:34:51,177 --> 1:34:55,8
when the elder has intellect...


1285
1:34:55,8 --> 1:34:57,65
and the younger man...


1286
1:34:57,65 --> 1:35:4,89
has all the joy, hope
and glamour of life before him.


1287
1:35:4,89 --> 1:35:9,161
That it should be so,
the world does not understand.


1288
1:35:9,161 --> 1:35:11,297
The world mocks at it...


1289
1:35:11,297 --> 1:35:34,253
and sometimes puts one
in the pillory for it.


1290
1:35:34,253 --> 1:35:37,423
The crime of which
you have been convicted...


1291
1:35:37,423 --> 1:35:39,625
is so bad...


1292
1:35:39,625 --> 1:35:43,28
that I shall pass
the severest sentence...


1293
1:35:43,28 --> 1:35:46,398
that the law will allow.


1294
1:35:46,398 --> 1:35:52,404
In my judgment, it is totally
inadequate for such a case as this.


1295
1:35:52,404 --> 1:35:55,608
It is the worst case
I have ever tried!


1296
1:35:55,608 --> 1:35:58,51
The sentence of the court...


1297
1:35:58,51 --> 1:36:0,813
is that you will be imprisoned...


1298
1:36:0,813 --> 1:36:4,183
<i>and held to hard labor...</i>


1299
1:36:4,183 --> 1:36:7,52
<i>- Stand aside, please.
- for two years.</i>


1300
1:36:7,52 --> 1:36:14,426
- Shame.
- Pervert.


1301
1:36:14,426 --> 1:36:22,801
Pervert!


1302
1:36:22,801 --> 1:36:45,124
Shame on you!


1303
1:36:45,124 --> 1:37:12,384
Disgusting!


1304
1:37:12,384 --> 1:37:15,788
<i>A slim thing,
gold-haired like an angel...</i>


1305
1:37:15,788 --> 1:37:18,324
<i>stands always at my side.</i>


1306
1:37:18,324 --> 1:37:22,261
<i>He moves in the gloom
like a white flower.</i>


1307
1:37:22,261 --> 1:37:43,82
<i>I thought but to defend him from
his father. I thought of nothing else.</i>


1308
1:37:43,82 --> 1:37:45,884
<i>Now my life seems
to have gone from me.</i>


1309
1:37:45,884 --> 1:37:48,32
<i>I'm caught in a terrible net.</i>


1310
1:37:48,32 --> 1:37:51,223
<i>But so long as I think
he is thinking of me...</i>


1311
1:37:51,223 --> 1:37:55,828
<i>my sweet rose, my delicate flower,
my lily of lilies...</i>


1312
1:37:55,828 --> 1:37:59,999
<i>it is in prison that I shall
test the power of love.</i>


1313
1:37:59,999 --> 1:38:3,302
<i>I shall see if I can't make
the bitter waters sweet...</i>


1314
1:38:3,302 --> 1:38:19,284
<i>by the intensity of the love
I bear you.</i>


1315
1:38:19,284 --> 1:38:23,722
<i>He asked me not to change.
Those were his last words to me...</i>


1316
1:38:23,722 --> 1:38:25,824
"Don't change."


1317
1:38:25,824 --> 1:38:30,596
Well, things are going to have
to change when he comes out.


1318
1:38:30,596 --> 1:38:32,898
He'll have no money at all.


1319
1:38:32,898 --> 1:38:35,701
- So you're blaming me, too, are you?
- I'm not blaming anyone.


1320
1:38:35,701 --> 1:38:40,472
Bosie, you're not the only person
on this earth Oscar cares about.


1321
1:38:40,472 --> 1:38:43,609
You've always hated me,
Robbie...


1322
1:38:43,609 --> 1:38:56,889
because Oscar loved and still loves me
when you were just one of his boys.


1323
1:38:56,889 --> 1:39:1,593
I'm suffering just as much
as he is, you know.


1324
1:39:1,593 --> 1:39:3,495
My life's ruined too.


1325
1:39:3,495 --> 1:39:8,67
I'm much younger than he is. I've hardly
had any life, and it's ruined already.


1326
1:39:8,67 --> 1:39:11,937
When Oscar gets out,
we'll live together properly.


1327
1:39:11,937 --> 1:39:15,808
We'll take a villa
somewhere near here... Posilipo...


1328
1:39:15,808 --> 1:39:20,546
- or Ischia.
- Or Capri.


1329
1:39:20,546 --> 1:39:23,82
I'll take care of him.


1330
1:39:23,82 --> 1:39:26,752
I'll give him
everything he wants.


1331
1:39:26,752 --> 1:39:31,256
I love him, Robbie.


1332
1:39:31,256 --> 1:39:50,542
Oscar's mine,
and I'm going to have him.


1333
1:39:50,542 --> 1:39:55,547
<i>"Years went over, and the giant
grew very old and very feeble.</i>


1334
1:39:55,547 --> 1:39:59,618
<i>He couldn't play about anymore,
so he sat in a huge armchair...</i>


1335
1:39:59,618 --> 1:40:7,86
<i>and watched the children at their games
and admired his garden.</i>


1336
1:40:7,86 --> 1:40:10,496
<i>'I have many beautiful flowers, '
he said.</i>


1337
1:40:10,496 --> 1:40:52,638
<i>'But the children are
the most beautiful flowers of all. "'</i>


1338
1:40:52,638 --> 1:40:56,875
I'm afraid Cyril has got
some idea why you're here.


1339
1:40:56,875 --> 1:41:2,114
I'm sending him
to school in Germany.


1340
1:41:2,114 --> 1:41:8,287
I can't manage them on my own.


1341
1:41:8,287 --> 1:41:11,19
Your back isn't better then?


1342
1:41:11,19 --> 1:41:14,86
No, not really.


1343
1:41:14,86 --> 1:41:19,198
I may have to have an operation.


1344
1:41:19,198 --> 1:41:22,868
What I've done
to you and the boys...


1345
1:41:22,868 --> 1:41:24,903
I can't...


1346
1:41:24,903 --> 1:41:30,275
I shall never forgive myself.


1347
1:41:30,275 --> 1:41:35,38
If we could choose
our natures...


1348
1:41:35,38 --> 1:41:37,649
If we could only choose.


1349
1:41:37,649 --> 1:41:42,554
But it's no use.


1350
1:41:42,554 --> 1:41:47,759
Whatever our natures are,
we must fulfill them...


1351
1:41:47,759 --> 1:41:49,962
or our lives... my life...


1352
1:41:49,962 --> 1:41:55,834
would have been filled
with dishonesty.


1353
1:41:55,834 --> 1:42:4,76
Even more dishonesty
than there actually was.


1354
1:42:4,76 --> 1:42:8,547
I've always loved you,
Constance.


1355
1:42:8,547 --> 1:42:12,317
You must believe me.


1356
1:42:12,317 --> 1:42:14,953
I don't see
how you can have done...


1357
1:42:14,953 --> 1:42:17,99
not truly.


1358
1:42:17,99 --> 1:42:19,958
Not if all the time...


1359
1:42:19,958 --> 1:42:24,529
I didn't know.


1360
1:42:24,529 --> 1:42:28,867
"Know thyself,"
I used to say.


1361
1:42:28,867 --> 1:42:33,38
I didn't know myself.


1362
1:42:33,38 --> 1:42:38,277
I didn't know.


1363
1:42:38,277 --> 1:42:43,81
I suppose you want a divorce.


1364
1:42:43,81 --> 1:42:48,287
You have every reason.


1365
1:42:48,287 --> 1:42:51,79
I've been thinking,
when you do come out...


1366
1:42:51,79 --> 1:42:54,76
when they let you out...
you can go to Switzerland or Italy...


1367
1:42:54,76 --> 1:42:58,83
write another play,
get yourself back.


1368
1:42:58,83 --> 1:43:1,5
You can.


1369
1:43:1,5 --> 1:43:14,946
You're so clever.
You can.


1370
1:43:14,946 --> 1:43:21,52
I don't want a divorce.


1371
1:43:21,52 --> 1:43:25,957
Will you ever let me
see the children again?


1372
1:43:25,957 --> 1:43:34,533
Of course.


1373
1:43:34,533 --> 1:43:40,405
But there must be one condition:


1374
1:43:40,405 --> 1:43:44,509
Oscar, you must never
see Bosie again.


1375
1:43:44,509 --> 1:43:52,918
If I saw Bosie now,
I'd kill him.


1376
1:43:52,918 --> 1:44:3,962
The children love you, Oscar.


1377
1:44:3,962 --> 1:44:15,44
They'll always love you.


1378
1:44:15,44 --> 1:44:18,9
Did anyone tell you?


1379
1:44:18,9 --> 1:44:29,588
<i>They've been performing
Salome in Paris.</i>


1380
1:44:29,588 --> 1:44:33,558
<i>"The giant hastened across the grass
and came near to the child.</i>


1381
1:44:33,558 --> 1:44:36,395
<i>And when he came quite close,
his face grew red with anger.</i>


1382
1:44:36,395 --> 1:44:40,932
<i>And he said,
'Who hath dared to wound thee? '</i>


1383
1:44:40,932 --> 1:44:44,236
<i>For on the palms of the child's hands
were the prints of two nails.</i>


1384
1:44:44,236 --> 1:45:3,255
<i>And the prints of two nails
were on his little feet.</i>


1385
1:45:3,255 --> 1:45:7,626
<i>'Who hath dared to wound thee? '
Cried the giant.</i>


1386
1:45:7,626 --> 1:45:11,496
<i>'Tell me, that I may take
my big sword and slay him. '</i>


1387
1:45:11,496 --> 1:45:13,832
<i>'Nay, 'answered the child.</i>


1388
1:45:13,832 --> 1:45:24,743
<i>'For these are
the wounds of love. "'</i>


1389
1:45:24,743 --> 1:45:27,379
Bosie thinks I'm jealous.


1390
1:45:27,379 --> 1:45:29,548
I think it will come as a shock
to Bosie to realize...


1391
1:45:29,548 --> 1:45:32,617
that even he is relatively unimportant
in the scheme of things.


1392
1:45:32,617 --> 1:45:36,721
But, no doubt, Bosie will be
remembered as long as Oscar...


1393
1:45:36,721 --> 1:45:43,929
unfortunately.


1394
1:45:43,929 --> 1:45:48,9
I sometimes wonder...


1395
1:45:48,9 --> 1:45:54,372
if I hadn't...


1396
1:45:54,372 --> 1:45:56,274
pushed him into...


1397
1:45:56,274 --> 1:45:59,244
Don't.


1398
1:45:59,244 --> 1:46:2,547
Oscar was very lucky
to meet you, Robbie.


1399
1:46:2,547 --> 1:46:5,584
Think who else
it might have been.


1400
1:46:5,584 --> 1:46:7,886
Oh, I'll have that one.
Thank you.


1401
1:46:7,886 --> 1:46:14,593
- Must you go abroad again at once?
- I shouldn't be here now.


1402
1:46:14,593 --> 1:46:17,729
But has he got anywhere to go
when he's released?


1403
1:46:17,729 --> 1:46:19,698
It'll have to be in France.


1404
1:46:19,698 --> 1:46:22,567
I'm going to see
what I can arrange.


1405
1:46:22,567 --> 1:46:24,87
But here...


1406
1:46:24,87 --> 1:46:32,844
when he leaves prison...


1407
1:46:32,844 --> 1:46:35,113
- Good-bye, Mr. Harris.
- Good-bye, sir.


1408
1:46:35,113 --> 1:46:43,522
Good-bye, Mr. Snow.
Thank you.


1409
1:46:43,522 --> 1:46:47,792
My dear Sphinx.


1410
1:46:47,792 --> 1:46:50,795
How marvelous of you to know what hat
to wear at 7:00 in the morning...


1411
1:46:50,795 --> 1:46:53,865
to meet a friend
who's been away.


1412
1:46:53,865 --> 1:46:56,902
- No, I'll keep this.
- What is it.


1413
1:46:56,902 --> 1:46:59,638
It's a letter to Bosie
telling him...


1414
1:46:59,638 --> 1:47:1,94
how I love him
but can never see him again.


1415
1:47:1,94 --> 1:47:4,976
I'm going to ask Robbie
to have it copied out before I send it.


1416
1:47:4,976 --> 1:47:8,446
I rather fear Bosie
might throw it on the fire.


1417
1:47:8,446 --> 1:47:46,952
<i>I call it De Profundis.
It comes from the very depths.</i>


1418
1:47:46,952 --> 1:47:49,487
<i>"I know not whether laws
be right...</i>


1419
1:47:49,487 --> 1:47:52,23
<i>or whether laws be wrong.</i>


1420
1:47:52,23 --> 1:47:54,259
<i>All that we know
who lie in jail...</i>


1421
1:47:54,259 --> 1:47:56,528
<i>is that the wall is strong...</i>


1422
1:47:56,528 --> 1:47:59,764
<i>and that each day
is like a year...</i>


1423
1:47:59,764 --> 1:48:6,871
<i>a year whose days are long.</i>


1424
1:48:6,871 --> 1:48:10,609
<i>Yet each man kills
the thing he loves.</i>


1425
